##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedFraction");
Context()->flags->set(requirePureFractions=>0);
Context()->flags->set(showMixedNumbers=>1);

@primes = (2, 3, 5, 7);
@multiples = (2,3,4,5,6);

do {

#Create two mixed numbers. Make sure some reductions will happen.
$den1Reduced = list_random(@primes);
$den2Reduced = list_random(@primes);

#$multiple1 goes into $num1 and $den2; $multiple2 goes into $num2 and $den1.
$multiple1=list_random(@multiples);
do {$multiple2=list_random(@multiples);} until ($multiple1!=$multiple2);

$den1 = $den1Reduced*$multiple2;
$den2 = $den2Reduced*$multiple1;

$num1 = $multiple1*random(2,10,1);
$num2 = $multiple2*random(2,10,1);

} until ( ($num1>$den1) && (gcd($num1,$den1)==1) && ($den2>$num2) && (gcd($num2,$den2)==1) );

$frac1 = Fraction($num1,$den1);
$frac2 = Fraction($den2,$num2);

$ans = (-$frac1 / $frac2)->reduce;
@ans = $ans->value;
$ansNum = abs($ans[0]);
$ansDen = $ans[1];

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML
Divide the following: [``[$frac1] \div \left( -[$frac2] \right) ``]

    [___________]{$ans} 

END_PGML

##############################################

$div1 = gcd($num1,$den2);
$div2 = gcd($num2,$den1);

$output1 = $ansDen==1 ? "$ans" : "-\frac{$ansNum}{$ansDen}";
$output2 = ((abs($ans)<1)||($ansDen==1)) ? "" : "If we like, we may convert this answer to a mixed number since the original factors were mixed numbers. ";

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

When we do fraction multiplication or division, if negative numbers are involved, it helps to first determine the sign (positive or negative) of the result. This way, when we carry out the fraction operation, we don't have to think about signs.

In this problem, we have:

    [`` \text{positive number} \div \text{negative number} = \text{negative number} ``]

Now we know the result must be negative, so we can move the negative sign to the front of the first fraction:

    [`` [$frac1] \div \left( -[$frac2] \right) = - [$frac1] \div [$frac2] ``]

Next, we do fraction division as usual, without the need to think about the negative sign.

We change both mixed numbers to improper fractions. In this case, the problem becomes

    [``-{\frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]}} \div \frac{[$den2]}{[$num2]}``]

Next, change division into multiplication, and, at the same time, flip the *second* fraction:

    [``-{\frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]}} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]}``]

Then we do fraction multiplication as usual. To avoid dealing with big numbers, we reduce fractions before doing multiplications. The full calculation is:

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   [$frac1] \div \left( -[$frac2] \right)
      &= - [$frac1] \div [$frac2] \\
      &= -{\frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]}} \div \frac{[$den2]}{[$num2]} \\
      &= -{\frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]}} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]} \\
      &= -{\frac{[$num1/$div1]}{[$den1/$div2]}} \cdot \frac{[$num2/$div2]}{[$den2/$div1]} \\
      &= [$output1]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

[$output2] The result is [`[$ans]`].

END_PGML_SOLUTION

